nal Map properties = new LinkedHashMap();\n        properties.put(\"labels\", new Object[] {new Object()});\n        properties.put(\"scores\", new Object[] {Integer.valueOf(1), \"not a number\"});\n\n        final int updatedProperties = convertor.setProps(bean, properties);\n\n        assertThat(updatedProperties).isZero();\n        assertThat(bean.getLabels()).isNull();\n        assertThat(bean.getScores()).isNull();\n    }\n\n    public static class SetterBean {\n        private String nullableText;\n        private int count;\n        private String[] labels;\n        private int[] scores;\n        private String plainText;\n\n        public String getNullableText() {\n            return nullableText;\n        }\n\n        public void setNullableText(final String nullableText) {\n            this.nullableText = nullableText;\n        }\n\n        public int getCount() {\n            return count;\n        }\n\n        public void setCount(final int count) {\n            this.count = count;\n        }\n\n        public String[] getLabels() {\n            return labels;\n        }\n\n        public void setLabels(final String[] labels) {\n            this.labels = labels;\n        }\n\n        public int[] getScores() {\n            return scores;\n        }\n\n        public void setScores(final int[] scores) {\n            this.scores = scores;\n        }\n\n        public String getPlainText() {\n            return plainText;\n        }\n\n        public void setPlainText(final String plainText) {\n            this.plainText = plainText;\n        }\n    }\n}\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1777941082684}}
[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing ArrayStoreException**\n\nI'm thinking about the ArrayStoreException and how it's a subclass of RuntimeException in Java, which complicates things. I realize I might need to assert counts and figure out how to handle cases with Integer[] being null. It seems like there's an issue with heap pollution if the array's runtime type is incompatible. I also wonder about Method.invoke and whether it logs failures when there's an argument type mismatch. It gets pretty complicated; I'm trying to wrap my head around it!\n\n**Exploring Method.invoke behavior**\n\nI'm analyzing how Method.invoke works in Java, particularly with varargs. When I pass an argument like `value`, it seems that there’s no automatic conversion from Object[] to int[]. On line 327, I notice the method parameter is of type Object, which complicates things regarding null _componentType. I think I might need to create a subclass, ExposedSetter, to manipulate this. By invoking the setter with value Object[] instead of a primitive array, I can test the public API effectively, though it feels a bit hacky!\n\n**Questioning validity of approach**\n\nI'm wondering if using Method and subclassing a public class is really valid, especially since it modifies protected fields directly, creating a state that's not typical for JSONPojoConvertor. I'm concerned about whether this approach offers high coverage—active call sites are useful, but the tests shouldn't feel forced or contrived. While the active class allows subclasses with public and protected fields, I think external library integration tests should ideally stick to the public API, which feels less desirable in this context.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0fc410b559300b820169f93a37c7908192995c4b5775e39513\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp-TpaH4aylv3LlG2SEb9ljSR43KgGuDazfAqKwIF3YPdpyBsi8G7rxHGFwhGOalfG633gf7GrqU_5IJy